m","Sculton, Burdeleys, Norfolk, Braintree, Essex, England":"Braintree, Essex, Anglie, United Kingdom","Wayland, Norfolk, England":"Wayland, Norfolk, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"about 1418–after 24 February 1476":"omkring 1418–efter 24. februar 1476","1418–1476":"fra10.januar1418til9.januar1419–fra10.januar1476til9.januar1477","1422–Female":"1422–Afdød","1444–1485":"1444–1485","1390–1460":"1390–1460","after 24 February 1476":"efter 24. februar 1476","about 1418":"omkring 1418","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","1422":"1422","1476":"fra 10. januar 1476 til 9. januar 1477","1485":"1485","after 1460":"efter 1460","1460":"1460","1418":"fra 10. januar 1418 til 9. januar 1419","1390":"1390","Herringby, Norfolk, England":"Herringby, Norfolk, England","Sculton Bordeleys, Norfolkshire, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Sculton, Burdeleys, Norfolk, Braintree, Essex, England":"Braintree, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Wayland, Norfolk, England":"Wayland, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1418–after 24 February 1476":"circa 1418–na 24 februari 1476","1418–1476":"van10januari1418to9januari1419–van10januari1476to9januari1477","1422–Female":"1422–Overleden","1444–1485":"1444–1485","1390–1460":"1390–1460","after 24 February 1476":"na 24 februari 1476","about 1418":"circa 1418","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","1422":"1422","1476":"van 10 januari 1476 to 9 januari 1477","1485":"1485","after 1460":"na 1460","1460":"1460","1418":"van 10 januari 1418 to 9 januari 1419","1390":"1390","Herringby, Norfolk, England":"Herringby, Norfolk, England","Sculton Bordeleys, Norfolkshire, England":"Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Sculton, Burdeleys, Norfolk, Braintree, Essex, England":"Braintree, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wayland, Norfolk, England":"Wayland, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1418–after 24 February 1476":"about 1418–after 24 February 1476","1418–1476":"from10January1418to9January1419–from10January1476to9January1477","1422–Female":"1422–Deceased","1444–1485":"1444–1485","1390–1460":"1390–1460","after 24 February 1476":"after 24 February 1476","about 1418":"about 1418","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","1422":"1422","1476":"from 10 January 1476 to 9 January 1477","1485":"1485","after 1460":"after 1460","1460":"1460","1418":"from 10 January 1418 to 9 January 1419","1390":"1390","Herringby, Norfolk, England":"Herringby, Norfolk, England","Sculton Bordeleys, Norfolkshire, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Sculton, Burdeleys, Norfolk, Braintree, Essex, England":"Braintree, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Wayland, Norfolk, England":"Wayland, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fenn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name in south-east England for someone who lived in a low-lying marshy area, from Middle English <i>fen(ne)</i> ‘fen, marsh’ (Old English <i>fenn</i>).","South German: topographic name from Old High German <i>fenni</i>, Middle Low German and Old Frisian <i>fenne</i> ‘bog’. Compare   Fehn  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 馮, see   Feng   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Fehn","meanings":["North German: topographic name for someone who lived by a bog or marsh, from <i>fehn</i> ‘bog’.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of the three farms in southeastern Norway named Fen, probably from Old Norse <i>Fávin</i>, of which the second element is <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’; the first element is unexplained."]},{"name":"Fenner","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>fen(ne)</i> ‘fen, marsh’ (Old English <i>fenn</i>) + <i>-er</i>, a topographic name for someone who lived in or by a marsh or fen. Fenn Place in Worth in Sussex had owners called <i>atte Fenne</i>, who in the time of King Henry VI (1421–1471) apparently changed their name to <i>Fenner</i>. See   Fenn  .","English: variant of <b>Fainer</b>, from Middle English <i>feiner</i>, <i>fener</i> ‘haymonger, one who sells hay’ (Old French <i>fenier</i>), or perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>feiner</i> ‘inventor; hypocrite’.","South German and Swiss German: occupational name for an ensign or standard bearer, from Middle High German <i>vener</i>, an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>vane</i> ‘flag’. See also   Fenrich  ."]},{"name":"Fenning","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>fen(ne)</i> ‘fen, marsh’ (Old English <i>fenn</i>) + <i>-ing</i>, for someone who lived by a fen or marsh. Compare   Fenn  ."]},{"name":"Finner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","German: topographic name from an agent derivative of Old High German <i>fenni</i>, Middle Low German and Old Frisian <i>fenne</i> ‘bog’ (see   Fenn  ).","German: ethnic name for a Finn (see   Finn   4)."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":37,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh Fenn was born about 1418, in England as the son of Thomas Fenn. He had at least 1 daughter with Eleanor. He died after 24 February 1476, in England, United Kingdom, and was buried in Herringby, Norfolk, England."},"et":{"about 1418–after 24 February 1476":"umbes 1418–pärast 24. veebruari 1476","1418–1476":"10.jaanuar1418kuni9.jaanuar1419–10.jaanuar1476kuni9.jaanuar1477","1422–Female":"1422–Surnud","1444–1485":"1444–1485","1390–1460":"1390–1460","after 24 February 1476":"pärast 24. veebruari 1476","about 1418":"umbes 1418","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","1422":"1422","1476":"10. jaanuar 1476 kuni 9. jaanuar 1477","1485":"1485","after 1460":"pärast 1460","1460":"1460","1418":"10. jaanuar 1418 kuni 9. jaanuar 1419","1390":"1390","Herringby, Norfolk, England":"Herringby, Norfolk, England","Sculton Bordeleys, Norfolkshire, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sculton, Burdeleys, Norfolk, Braintree, Essex, England":"Braintree, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wayland, Norfolk, England":"Wayland, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1418–after 24 February 1476":"noin 1418–24. helmikuuta 1476 jälkeen","1418–1476":"vuodesta10.tammikuuta1418vuoteen9.tammikuuta1419–vuodesta10.tammikuuta1476vuoteen9.ta